## 4. MDX Frontmatter Rules

Keep the frontmatter structure.

Update only language-dependent values.

For English:

lang: "en"

For Japanese:

lang: "ja"

Translate only:

- title
- description

Do not translate:

- category
- tags
- status
- visibility
- translationKey
- date

Example Korean title:

title: "2026년 4월 29일, 프로젝트 전반의 개발 진행 상황 정리"

English title example:

title: "Project Development Progress Overview as of April 29, 2026"

Japanese title example:

title: "2026年4月29日時点のプロジェクト全体の開発進捗整理"

Keep the category value as:

category: "projects"

Keep tags as technical identifiers.
Do not translate tag values unless explicitly instructed.

---

## 5. English Style Guide

When translating into English:

- Use natural maker / developer log style.
- Keep the writing simple but thoughtful.
- Avoid dramatic startup language.
- Avoid overly formal corporate writing.
- Use clear and calm expressions.

Prefer expressions like:

- At this stage
- For now
- The next challenge is
- This is not a finished conclusion, but a record of where things stand now.
- The direction is becoming clearer.
- There are still several issues to work through.
- I want to leave this as a record of the current state.

The English should feel like a personal project progress note, not a press release.

---

## 6. Japanese Style Guide

When translating into Japanese:

- Use natural Japanese record-style writing.
- Avoid overly stiff business Japanese.
- Keep the tone calm and readable.
- Use polite but not excessively formal language.
- Avoid sounding like a company announcement.
- Keep the feeling of a personal development log.

Prefer expressions like:

- 現時点では
- 今の段階では
- まずは〜を中心に進めている
- まだ完成した状態ではない
- 今後の課題として見えている
- この記録は、現時点での整理として残しておきたい
- 少しずつ方向性が見えてきた
- まだ答えが出ているわけではない

The Japanese should feel like a personal development log written naturally by a builder.

